defaultHow effectively do Community Transport services address the needs of passengerdefault in isolated communities? How could Community Transport be improved?default&#xa0;defaultThe County Council’s definition of Commun
defaultity Transport is not restricted
default to Voluntary Social Cars and Community Minibus schemes run under either Section 22 or Section 19 Permits.  It als
defaulto includes demand-responsive transport provided by Commercial Transport Operators under the umbrella of 
defaultits 
defaultRural Wheels Scheme.  The Rural Wheels scheme provides a flexible transport service which only receives financial support when it operates.  This is
default cost effective from the Council’s perspective when compared with the relatively high cost of supporting bus services particularly in more remote rural areas where there are few people travelling.  
defaultThe County Council is only able
default to support the statutory c
defaultoncessionary travel scheme so concessions are only available on scheduled bus services.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe provision of Community Transport other than the Rural Wheels type services relies heavily on volunteers which are easier to recruit in some parts of the county tha
defaultn in others.   The volunteers are required
default to both drive
default and 
defaultcoordinate requests within
default schemes.  Experience has shown when community transport schemes have started to pay staff they have soon become unviable. The development of the Rural Wheels scheme acr
defaultoss the County has meant that the Council facilitates/supports transport in all areas irrespective of the availability of volunteers.  The development and ongoing support of Community Transport requires both financial and staffing suppor
defaultt to achieve the be
defaultst results.  
defaultIn this respect the County Council works closely with communities to develop schemes.
default&#xa0;defaultFurther flexibility in the S19 permit legislation could improve community transport. Such transport schemes can presently only be used by members of the sch
defaulteme and are not available to the “general public” which prevents use by tourists and visitors. 
defaultThe County Council is developing a new community transport solution “Community Wheels” which will deliver demand-
defaultresponsive
default transport using fully accessible comm
defaultunity minibuses in partnership with local communities.  The viability of such services could be increased if visitors were able to have some sort of temporary membership that would allow them to pay to use the service. 
default&#xa0;
defaultOpening out membership could increa
defaultse the patronage and therefore viability of some type of community minibus schemes.   However, this could cause
default tensions
default with the small commercial provider taxi who would normally provide transport where scheduled bus services or other transport was not av
defaultailable.  The County Council relies heavily on the availability of a large number of small operators to provide transport for children with special needs and social care clients.
